## Introducing Today's Project!

### What is Amazon VPC?

Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) is a service that enables you to create a private, isolated network within AWS where you can launch and manage cloud resources. It provides complete control over your networking configuration, including IP addresses, subnets, routing, and security rules. and it is useful because it allows you to securely organize and protect your resources, control how they communicate with each other and the internet, and build scalable, highly available cloud architectures that meet different application and security requirements.

### How I used Amazon VPC in this project

In today's project, I used Amazon VPC to establish VPC peering between two separate Virtual Private Clouds, enabling resources in each VPC to communicate securely using private IP addresses. I configured the VPC peering connection, updated the route tables to direct traffic between the VPCs, and verified connectivity by testing communication between EC2 instances in the different VPCs. This exercise demonstrated how VPC peering provides seamless and secure networking across isolated AWS environments without requiring internet access or a VPN.


### One thing I didn't expect in this project was...

One thing I didn't expect in this project was that creating a VPC peering connection alone would not enable communication between the VPCs. I learned that I also needed to update the route tables on both sides to direct traffic through the peering connection. This reinforced the importance of proper routing configuration in AWS networking.


### This project took me...

This project took me about 2 hours to complete, including setting up the VPC peering connection, configuring the route tables, troubleshooting connectivity issues, and verifying communication between the EC2 instances.


